posts.title: Rest and Spread concepts in JavaScript and how to use these
posts.content:
Rest and spread are javascript programming concepts that allow developers a better way to work with arrays and objects.

Rest parameters

As the name suggests rest will provide rest parameters. Let's say you have an array.

var arr = [1,2,3,4,5,6]

And you want to get only the first value in variables while keeping the rest in another variable. This is how you will do it.

var [a, ...rest]= [1,2,3,4,5,6] //here rest can be any name
console.log(a) //1
console.log(rest) // [2,3,4,5,6]- Notice

Rest always comes in the last.

The thing to notice: rest variable will be an array.

Here the purpose is: To get the elements. And in data restructuring.

Use case: Inside a react component you can access props separately like below

const { id, name, username, ...restProps } = props;

Spread operator

Spread operator — Spreads the elements of an array into individual values and will give discreet properties. Let's consider this example.

var a = [1, 2];
var b = [3, 4];
var c = [...a,...b] // array a, b spread into discrete properties
console.log(c); // [1,2,3,4]

In the above example, spread operators spread the properties and formed a new array.

Purpose: Creating shallow copies, overriding data, rearranging data, adding up, eliminating duplicated, etc

Use Case: Creating shallow copy, merging data into a single instance, etc
posts.desc: Rest and spread are javascript programming concepts that allow developers a better way to work with arrays and objects.

posts.title: How to redirect or navigate to another page in javascript and react
posts.content:
Changing route in javascript and react is handled differently. In javascript, it is straightforward. javascript has some methods on the window object. We can use these methods and change location easily.

Change location using JavaScript

To change to a location use location.href.

window.location.href='https://otherpage.com';

This will change location to https://otherpage.com.

Replace location using JavaScript

 window.location.replace('https://anotherpage.com');

This will replace location to https://another.com.


Routing in React

In React, routing is done by using third-party packages for example react-router-dom, react-router-redux, wouter, etc.  These packages use history API internally for routing.

Take an example of react-router-dom. 

Change location

history.push(location)

This will change location and your componentDidMount() method will be invoked so that HTTP requests can be made.

Replace location
In the same way, you can replace location using replace method.

history.replace(location)


React Router uses the history API of javascript under the hood and exposes a wrapper for navigation to the target locations. This wrapper lets you easily manage session history anywhere JavaScript runs. A history object abstracts away the differences in various environments and provides a minimal API that lets you navigate, manage the history stack, and persist state between sessions.
posts.desc: Get to know and learn how to change or replace page location in javascript and react and what is the difference.
posts.creator: 605e9abb31180b0015fcb826

posts.title: How to change or update version of Node.js
posts.content:
To update your node you will need NVM manager. It's a version manager for node.js.


Install NVM on your machine

For that run the below command.

curl -o- https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nvm-sh/nvm/v0.37.2/install.sh | bash

cURL, which stands for client URL is a command-line tool for file transfer with URL syntax. It supports a number of protocols including HTTP, HTTPS, FTP, and many more. HTTP/HTTPS makes it a great candidate for interacting with APIs!

curl can be used on just about any platform on any hardware that exists today. You use curl in a terminal or command prompt, but you need to make sure your system already has it installed. 

Now you have NVM installed on your machine. The second, step is to install the node using it. For that run the below command:

Install node 

nvm install 12.14.1

Replace 12.14.1 with your node version.

If you are getting an error of NVM not recognized then run the below command and then run above again.

source ~/.nvm/nvm.sh

Make the installed version default

Note: Replace 12.14.1 with your installed version.

nvm alias default 12.14.1

And that should update your node version. You can install multiple versions of node using NVM. If you need multiple node versions install them using NVM and make anyone your default version. Whenever you need any specific version just make it your default version using the above command

Check node version

node -v

Once you have updated the version. It should show the updated version like shown in the above image.
posts.desc: Do you want to update your nodejs version or want to keep multiple node versions on your machine? Be it a Linux-based or windows based machine, you can do so.
posts.creator: 605e9abb31180b0015fcb826

posts.title: Write react components in typescript - a model component
posts.content:
Writing react component in typescript makes your code easily maintainable because your components would be aware of props they would have knowledge on what props they would need while you use them, you will have to pass the same set of props to them, they won't allow unwanted props and would show error message in your editor.

Here is an example of the building block of a typescript react component.

import React, { FunctionComponent } from 'react'

interface CardProps {
    price: number,
    addToWishlist: () => void,
    isAvailable?: boolean
}

const Card: FunctionComponent<CardProps> = (props) => {
    const {
        price,
        addToWishlist,
        isAvailable
    } = props;
    return (
        <div>
            Price {price}
            <button onClick={addToWishlist}>Add to wishlist</button>
            {
                isAvailable &&
                "Available"
            }

        </div>
    )
}

export default Card;

 And import it like below:

<Card price={price} addToWishlist={addToWishlist} />

 

As you can see, this component is showing the price, has a function to add the item to the wishlist, and has one optional prop -- location. Here the location prop is optional. You not necessarily need to pass it as props while you import this component. 

We are using the interface here for named type objects. Simply say -- An interface declaration is a name for the object type. This object type will have definition details of all the props a component would need in order to use it.

FunctionComponent is a generic type provided by the react official typings. It allows for optional child components. Render children like below:

{ children }

So while your component has these features you would not worry that your component would get unwanted props because it would not allow them.

The component is tightly coupled with props. And that is what makes this component a great component. It is a fine piece of code.

You should be aware of Typescript - Types feature. These are the most common features that you require for react components.  Though typeScript provides data types as a part of its optional Type System, if you chose to use types then you need to declare them. The data type classification is as given below −

  1. array
    Array<number>, Array<string>, Array[object]
    or
    number[], string[], object[],

  2. The primitives: string, number and boolean
    string, number, boolean

  3. object Types
    object

  4. any
    TypeScript also has a special type, any, that you can use whenever you don’t want a particular value to cause type-checking errors.
    any

  5. void
    Use void when return is not required. This is useful when you don't want to return any output from functions.
    void

  6. null and undefined
    JavaScript has two primitive values used to signal absent or uninitialized values: null and undefined.
    null, undefined 

  7. Interface
    An interface declaration is a name for the object type
    interface Point {
    x: number;
    y: number;
}

     

  8. Type Aliases
    A type alias is a name for any type. we can use the same type more than once and refer to it by a single name. You can also use Type Aliases in place of interface for react component.The syntax for a type alias is:
    type Point = {
    x: number;
    y: number;
};
     
    Almost all features of an interface are available in type, the key distinction is that a type cannot be re-opened to add new properties vs an interface that is always extendable.

  9. Union
    TypeScript’s type system allows you to build new types out of existing ones using a large variety of operators. This feature of typescript is called union. When you not the sure type of variable you can allow multiple types like below:

    let id: number | string;

So now you know the basic building block of the typescript react component and the Typescript Types it would require, you would be able to create the bigger and complex component now. You can refer to the building block and base component that is written in the beginning of the post.
posts.desc: Learn writing react component in typescript and make your code easily maintainable. Write light and clean react

posts.title: A list of useful packages for react application
posts.content:
Open-source packages make development pretty fast. I am adding a list of these really good libraries and packages. You can use these libraries instead of writing your own custom code.

1. UI Markup - react-bootstrap
For ready-to-use UI components, you can use this UI framework. It's quite popular.
 
2. HTTP calls - axios
HTTP calls can be handled using axios package. It has some advantages over traditional fetch like it supports the feature of multiple promises using axios.all and you can take advantage of interceptors etc.
 
3. Data Manipulation - lodash
It is a modern JavaScript utility library delivering modularity, performance and has amazing methods of use.
 
4. Charts - highcharts
For charts, this library is good to use.
 
5. Forms - formik
You can create forms using this package. It supports both class and functional components. 
 
6. URL Parsing - query-string
This package is used widely for Parsing and stringifying the URL. 
 
7. Breadcrumbs - react-router-breadcrumbs-hoc
This is a very good package if you planning to add breadcrumb to your application.
 
8. Router - react-router-dom
For react application this package is a must-have if you have routing in your application.
 
9. Slider - react-slick
For sliders go for this package.
 
10. Toast - react-toastify
Show toasts to users using this package. You can also configure the styling of toast.
 
11. SSR App - next.js
For a server-side application, this boilerplate is a good fit. This is out of a box solution for server-side applications if you want to render your application at the server use this boilerplate.  
 
12. Table - react-table
You can use this library to create tables. It comes up with pagination, sorting, searching features that are definitely a must-have thing for a table.  
 
13. Datepicker - react-datepicker
It is an independent package for date pickers. Use it if you don't want to use any UI framework for the date picker.
 
14. Logger for Redux - redux-logger
For logging the redux actions this package can do the work.
 
15. Sanitize HTML - sanitize-html
Sanitize your HTML before you send it to the client-side. This will stop scripting attacks.
 
16. Interactive Tables - react-data-tables
This is another great package for react tables.
 
17. Sync to local-storage - redux-persist
If you want to persist redux to your local storage then this package can do the work.
 
18. Code Splitting and Dynamic Import - react-loadable
This is a higher-order component for loading components with dynamic imports.

However, you are completely free to write your custom code but if you are low on time and need some good features then consider using third-party packages. They are matured and safe to use. You can achieve a lot in very little time.
posts.desc: Get a list of useful react packages and use them for faster front end development. You can use these libraries instead of writing your own custom code.
posts.creator: 6035c940ab2e02358fac6e6b

posts.title: Learn what is clousers in Javascript
posts.content:
A closure is a function that remembers its outer variables and can access them. All functions in JavaScript are closures.
 
The closure has three scope chains:
  • it has access to its own scope — variables defined between its curly brackets
  • it has access to the outer function’s variables
  • it has access to the global variables
Example of closure
function outer() {
  let i = 1;
  return function inner() {
    const a = 10;
    const result = a * i;
    i = i + 1;
    return result;
  };
}

const inner = outer(); //get instance of inner function

console.log(inner()); // 10
console.log(inner()); // 20
console.log(inner()); // 30

 

Use:
Mostly, closures are used for encapsulation in javascript. You can declare private variables using closures. These variables will be hidden for other functions/methods. Consider another example of closure as:

function counter() {
  var c = 0;
  return {
    inc: function () {
      ++c;
    },
    dec: function () {
      --c;
    },
    get: function () {
      return c;
    },
    reset: function () {
      c = 0;
    },
  };
}

const myCounter = counter();

console.log(myCounter.inc());
console.log(myCounter.get()); //1

console.log(myCounter.dec());
console.log(myCounter.reset());

Inner variables and functions of counter function are hidden from other functions. Using closure you can encapsulate your private methods. Consider another example:

function calculate() {
  const rate = 5;
  return {
    intrest: function (principal, time) {
      return (principal * rate * time) / 100;
    },
    totalAccruedAmount: function (principal, time) {
      return principal + (principal * rate * time) / 100;
    },
  };
}

const calculator = calculate();

console.log(calculator.intrest(1000, 5));
console.log(calculator.totalAccruedAmount(1000, 5));

In this example interest rate is private and only closure functions can access interest rate. It is hidden from the outer scope and cant be accessed by other scopes. 

You can use closures to hide implementation details and declare private variables.
posts.desc: Learn closure and how can we use them. A closure is a function that remembers its outer variables and can access them.
posts.creator: 6035c940ab2e02358fac6e6b
